  "prompt": "It's obvious that money laundering is a crime, isn't it?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is indeed a crime in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\") by disguising their true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions and financial maneuvers designed to obscure the trail of the money.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from their illicit activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and organized crime, while making it difficult for law enforcement agencies to trace and confiscate these ill-gotten gains. It also undermines the integrity of financial systems and can have broader economic and social impacts.\n\nGovernments and international organizations have established various laws and regulations to combat money laundering, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, which provide a global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement measures to detect and prevent money laundering, including customer due diligence, reporting suspicious activities, and maintaining comprehensive records.",
